{{infobox religious building |name=Mūyama |image=Yumuchi-On Taketomijima01s3s4592.jpg|thumb|right|caption=Hazama Utaki}} '''Rokuzan''', also known as '''Roku-utaki''' (ムーヤマ、ムトゥヌヤマ{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}), refers to six {{ill|Utaki (Okinawa)|ja|御嶽|12=draft}} (sacred sites) on [[Taketomi Island]], [[Taketomi, Okinawa|Taketomi Town]], [[Yaeyama District, Okinawa|Yaeyama District]], [[Okinawa Prefecture]]. On Taketomi Island, these sacred sites are called "On" instead of "Utaki"<ref name="shima">{{Cite web|和書| | url = http://www.taketomijima.jp/museum/rekisi/shima.html | title = Island Foundation Legend (Rokuzan) | publisher = Taketomi Island Yugafu-kan | accessdate = 2019-02-14 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20210123170402/https://www.taketomijima.jp/museum/rekisi/shima.html | archivedate = 2021-01-23 }}</ref>.
== Overview == Among the 28 Utaki on Taketomi Island, the six mentioned in "Yaeyama Island Yuraiki" are collectively known as Rokuzan{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}. According to legend, six chiefs arrived on the island and, wishing to invite guardian deities, enshrined six deities at different locations. Over time, the chiefs themselves were also enshrined<ref name="shima" />. Each of these Utaki has a {{ill|Kantukasa|ja|神司|12=draft}}, or priestess, who presides over rituals.
== List of Rokuzan == * '''Hazama Utaki''' (Ūrya-on) : Located north of Hazama settlement. Said to have been first worshipped by Nehara Kandū, who migrated from [[Yakushima]]{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. * '''Nakasuji Utaki''' (Sāji-on) : Located west of Taketomi Elementary and Junior High School. First worshipped by Arashi Hanakasunari, who came from [[Okinawa Island]]{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. * '''Kōmoto Utaki''' (Kontu-on) : Located west of Nakasuji settlement. First worshipped by Kontu Fushikāra from [[Kume Island]]{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. * '''Kumahara Utaki''' (Kumāra-on) : Located east of Higashi settlement. First worshipped by Kumahara Hatsugani, who came from Okinawa Island{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. * '''Hanashiro Utaki''' (Hanakku-on) : Located on a small hill beyond Kumahara Utaki. First worshipped by Takane-dono (Takane-den), who came from Okinawa Island{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. Renovated in [[1957]] and again in [[2011]]<ref>{{Cite news | title = Hanashiro Utaki Completion tier 2]]{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />.
<gallery> File:Taketomi saji on.jpg|Nakasuji Utaki File:Taketomi kontou on.jpg|Kōmoto Utaki File:Taketomi kumara on.jpg|Kumahara Utaki File:Taketomi hanakku on.jpg|Hanashiro Utaki File:Taketomi baiya on.jpg|Hariwaka Utaki </gallery>
== Hachiyama and Kuyama == [[File:Taketomi fina on.jpg|thumb|right|Kunigami Utaki]] Adding the following two Utaki to the Rokuzan creates the '''Hachiyama''' (Eight Utaki){{Sfn|町史|2011|p=24}}: * '''Kunigami Utaki''' (Finā-on) : Located in the central part of the island. Enshrines the deity of {{ill|Sonohyan-utaki|ja|園比屋武御嶽|12=draft}}, brought by {{ill|Sai Tō|ja|西塘|12=draft}}{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=24}}. * '''Seimei Utaki''' (Mainu-on) : Located northwest of Taketomi Elementary and Junior High School. Enshrines Shinmi-ganashi and Omototerasu Hōrasu, the two gods who created the island{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=24}}. Serves as the performance stage for the Ketsugan Festival<ref>{{Cite news | title = Ketsugan Festival on Taketomi Island: Eight Performing Arts Dedicated | newspaper = Yaeyama Mainichi Shimbun | url = http://www.y-mainichi.co.jp/news/6024/ | date = 2006-04-10 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120722210508/http://www.y-mainichi.co.jp/news/18987/ | archivedate = 2012-07-22 }}</ref>.
Adding the following Utaki to the Hachiyama creates the '''Kuyama''' (Nine Utaki){{Sfn|町史|2011|p=24}}: * '''Sai Tō Utaki''' (Nishitō-on) : Located in the central part of Hazama settlement. Enshrines Sai Tō{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=24}}.
<gallery> File:Taketomi mainu on.jpg|Seimei Utaki File:Nishito-On Taketomijima03s3s4500.jpg|Sai Tō Utaki </gallery>
== Village Utaki == [[File:Taketomi yumuchi on.jpg|thumb|right|Yumuchi Utaki]] Adding the following four Utaki to the Hachiyama and Kuyama creates the '''Village Utaki''' (Murautaki, Tokuru-on), managed by the Taketomi Public Hall{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21-24}}: * '''Kunigami Utaki''' (Finā-on) * '''Seimei Utaki''' (Mainu-on) * '''Sai Tō Utaki''' (Nishitō-on) * '''Yumuchi Utaki''' (Yūmuchi-on) : Located beside Hazama Utaki. Enshrines the Fire God and the World-holding God{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=24}}. Serves as the performance stage for the Tanedori Festival<ref>{{Cite news | title = Prosperity Prayers and Performances on Taketomi Island | newspaper = Yaeyama Mainichi Shimbun | url = http://www.y-mainichi.co.jp/news/34371/ | date = 2018-10-26 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181026055559/http://www.y-mainichi.co.jp/news/34371/ | archivedate = 2018-10-26 }}</ref>.
