{{infobox religious building |name=Mūyama |image=Yumuchi-On Taketomijima01s3s4592.jpg|thumb|right|caption=Hazama Utaki}} '''Rokuzan''', also known as '''Roku-utaki''' (ムーヤマ、ムトゥヌヤマ{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}), refers to six {{ill|Utaki (Okinawa)|ja|御嶽|12=draft|12=draft}} (sacred sites) on [[Taketomi Island]], [[Taketomi, Okinawa|Taketomi Town]], [[Yaeyama District, Okinawa|Yaeyama District]], [[Okinawa Prefecture]]. On Taketomi Island, these sacred sites are called "On" instead of "Utaki"<ref name="shima">{{Cite web|和書| | url = http://www.taketomijima.jp/museum/rekisi/shima.html | title = Island Foundation Legend (Rokuzan) | publisher = Taketomi Island Yugafu-kan | accessdate = 2019-02-14 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20210123170402/https://www.taketomijima.jp/museum/rekisi/shima.html | archivedate = 2021-01-23 }}</ref>.
== Overview == Among the 28 Utaki on Taketomi Island, the six mentioned in "Yaeyama Island Yuraiki" are collectively known as Rokuzan{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}. According to legend, six chiefs arrived on the island and, wishing to invite guardian deities, enshrined six deities at different locations. Over time, the chiefs themselves were also enshrined<ref name="shima" />. Each of these Utaki has a {{ill|Kantukasa|ja|神司|12=draft|12=draft}}, or priestess, who presides over rituals.
== List of Rokuzan == * '''Hazama Utaki''' (Ūrya-on) : Located north of Hazama settlement. Said to have been first worshipped by Nehara Kandū, who migrated from [[Yakushima]]{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. * '''Nakasuji Utaki''' (Sāji-on) : Located west of Taketomi Elementary and Junior High School. First worshipped by Arashi Hanakasunari, who came from [[Okinawa Island]]{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. * '''Kōmoto Utaki''' (Kontu-on) : Located west of Nakasuji settlement. First worshipped by Kontu Fushikāra from [[Kume Island]]{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. * '''Kumahara Utaki''' (Kumāra-on) : Located east of Higashi settlement. First worshipped by Kumahara Hatsugani, who came from Okinawa Island{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. * '''Hanashiro Utaki''' (Hanakku-on) : Located on a small hill beyond Kumahara Utaki. First worshipped by Takane-dono (Takane-den), who came from Okinawa Island{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />. Renovated in [[1957]] and again in [[2011]]<ref>{{Cite news | title = Hanashiro Utaki Completion tier 2]]{{Sfn|町史|2011|p=21}}<ref name="shima" />.
